{This is awkward. With 8 points you must respond, but you cannot bid a new suit at the 2-level without 11 or more. Although you are far from balanced you must say 1NT.

You might as well not have worried. Partner jumps to 4\S and you pass.

North would play 4\S.

Click 

South plays 4\S. West leads the \HK.

<b>South plays 4\S. West leads the \HK.</b>

Losers: \S ? : \H 0 : \D 1 : \C 0 : Total = ?

That 1 \D loser is definite. So instead of guessing how many \S losers you have, just approach it from the viewpoint that you can afford 2 but not 3.

If the missing \Ss split 3-3 then your life is easy. You play \SA, then any \S. Win their return and play any \S. The defense can win two \Ss but no more.

It's when the \Ss are splitting 4-2 that you must be careful. If somebody has \S K Q 9 3 for example you will go down. The one important distribution to guard against is a doubleton honor in one hand. In this case your second \S play must be a <b>LOW</b> \S. When this drives out one honor your \S J 10 can insure that only one more trick is lost.

If your second \S play is the \SJ East will win the \SK and West will be able to take two more tricks with his \S Q 9 because you have the \S 10 7 left.

But if your second \S play is a small \S East will win the \SK and you will be left with the \S J 10 to deal with West's \S Q 9, holding him to just one more trick.}
[Play "W"]HK

